<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1965-08-16T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1965-08-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="157" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d157">
                        <head>157. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_TJC1" type="from">James C.
                                Thomson</persName>, Jr., of the National Security Council Staff to
                            the Presidentʼs Special Assistant for National Security Affairs
                                (<persName corresp="#p_BWP1" type="to">Bundy</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d157fn1">Source: Johnson Library, National
                                Security File, Name File, Cooper. Secret.</note>
                        </head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1965-08-16">August 16, 1965</date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <list type="subject">
                            <head>SUBJECT</head>
                            <item>The Week in Asia</item>
                        </list>
                        <p>[Here follows information on Vietnam, Burma, and Japan.]</p>
                        <p rend="flushleft">
                            <hi rend="italic">Cambodia</hi>
                        </p>
                        <p>[<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line of source text not declassified</hi>]
                            has accidentally uncovered anti-Sihanouk Khmer Serei leader Son Ngoc
                            Thanh somewhere in Saigon, now wants to establish a dialogue. State is
                            properly skittish as this guy has the political future of Harold Stassen
                            but drives <persName corresp="#p_SPN1">Sihanouk</persName> crazy. We are
                            permitting one or two more “contacts” with him—but we may be risking a
                            further Cambodia blow-up (our relations with <persName corresp="#p_SPN1">Sihanouk</persName> are currently euphoric relative to the recent
                            past).</p>
                        <p>[Here follows information on Taiwan and Singapore.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName>
                                    <hi rend="strong">T</hi>
                                </persName><note n="2" xml:id="d157fn2">Initialed by <persName corresp="#p_TJC1">Thomson</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_RDW1">Donald Ropa</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_CCL1">Chester Cooper</persName>.</note>
                                <persName>RC</persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>